SIMPLE: preach
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preach
<hw>Preach</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Preached</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Preaching</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>prechen</ets>, OF. <ets>preechier</ets>, F.
<ets>pr⟦ecir⟧cher</ets>, fr. L. <ets>praedicare</ets> to cry in public,
to proclaim; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>dicare</ets> to make known,
<ets>dicere</ets> to say; or perhaps from (assumed) LL.
<ets>praedictare</ets>. See <er>Diction</er>, and cf.
<er>Predicate</er>, <er>Predict</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
proclaim or publish tidings; specifically, to proclaim the gospel; to
discourse publicly on a religious subject, or from a text of Scripture;
to deliver a sermon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How shall they <qex>preach</qex>, except they be sent?</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. x. 15.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From that time Jesus began to <qex>preach</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. iv. 17.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give serious advice on morals or religion; to
discourse in the manner of a preacher.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Preach
<hw>Preach</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To proclaim by public
discourse; to utter in a sermon or a formal religious
harangue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That Cristes gospel truly wolde <qex>preche</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord hath anointed me to <qex>preach</qex> good tidings unto
the meek.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. lxi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To inculcate in public discourse; to urge with
earnestness by public teaching.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I have <xex>preached</xex>
righteousness in the great congregation.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Ps. xl.
9.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deliver or pronounce; <as>as, to <ex>preach</ex>
a sermon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To teach or instruct by preaching; to inform by
preaching.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧As ye are
<xex>preached</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Southey.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To advise or recommend earnestly.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My master <qex>preaches</qex> patience to him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To preach down</b></col>, <cd>to oppress, or humiliate by
preaching.</cd> <au>Tennyson.</au> -- <col><b>To preach up</b></col>,
<cd>to exalt by preaching; to preach in support of; <as>as, <ex>to
preach up</ex> equality</as>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preach</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Preach
<hw>Preach</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F. <ets>pr⟦ecir⟧che</ets>, fr.
<ets>pr⟦ecir⟧cher</ets>. See <er>Preach</er>, <pos>v.</pos>]</ety>
<def>A religious discourse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Preacher</ent>⟦br⟧
